### Solution:
This is a simple case of **DP** technique.  I first considered a 2-state problem where I have to determine if I should buy the bike or not.
> In the first part I bought the bike.
> In the 2nd part I didn't get paid enough and in other words I don't have enough money to buy the bike.

If you go through the problem statement I don't have access to the data.  However, the question could be formulated such that I know the numbers of animals I have before.

It is now easy to find out my total number of animals and animals without legs then it gets trivial to find the number of animals with legs if I know my total number of animals.

### Time Complexity
This problem has to do with the problem of recursion and then the running of the computation.  In the first part I used the recursive method to compute my number of animals with legs in other words I'll use the same procedure for two different cases, one where I buy the bike, other where I don't.  This will take me n calls to the function to arrive at my final answer.
The running time is thus `O(2^n)` where n is the number of calls to the recursive routine.

The cost of the recursive call is negligible and this is `O(1)` as well.
So the running cost is simply `O(2^N)`

### Space Complexity
This is again quite simple.  If I take the number of calls to be n, then I'll need another n space in my memory, so my total memory complexity for both cases `O(2*n)`

Hope this helps!  Thanks.
